The Chinese character (kanji) â€œwazawaiâ€ or â€œsaiâ€ (ç½) has been named the kanji
that best symbolizes the year 2018 for Japan. The kanji is unveiled each year
at historic Kiyomizu Temple in Kyoto. Screencap from [ANN News official
YouTube Channel](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X1zI5QwOXqY).

After a year of earthquakes, torrential rains, floods, typhoons and torrid
heat, the Chinese character meaning â€œdisasterâ€ (
[ç½](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%81%BD#Definitions): â€œwazawaiâ€ or â€œsaiâ€)
was named as Japan's â€œ2018 Kanji of the Yearâ€. Chinese characters are known as
kanji (æ¼¢å­—) in Japan.

This year's kanji was selected by the [Japanese Kanji Proficiency
Society](http://www.kanken.or.jp/kanji2018/) based on the results of a
nationwide poll conducted earlier in the fall. Of the 193,214 entries
submitted from all Japan, â€œwazawaiâ€ received the most ballots at 20,858.

Throughout 2018, Japan endured a steady series of hammer blows, including:

  * A [massive snowfall](https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/04/18/national/seven-eleven-store-owner-claims-chain-forced-stay-open-fukui-blizzard-union/#.XBSknHRKhhE) that all but shut down towns along the Japan Sea coast for nearly a week
  * An [earthquake in June](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Osaka_earthquake) that seriously damaged some parts of Osaka and neighboring cities
  * [Widespread deadly flooding](https://globalvoices.org/2018/07/12/questions-swirl-over-japanese-governments-response-to-deadly-unprecedented-rains/) in July after much of western Japan received incredible amounts of torrential rain that broke all historical records
  * [Record-breaking heat](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44935152) for much of the summer that resulted in dozens of deaths
  * Another [earthquake in September](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Hokkaido_Eastern_Iburi_earthquake), this time in southern Hokkaido, that left millions without power for up to three days and disrupted the economy of the island
  * The [strongest typhoon in 25 years](https://globalvoices.org/2018/09/11/strongest-typhoon-to-hit-japan-in-25-years-largely-forgotten-following-massive-earthquake/), which shut down Osaka's main international airport for nearly a week

[In a news
release](https://www.kanken.or.jp/kanji2018/common/data/release_kanji2018.pdf),
the Kyoto-based Japanese Kanji Proficiency Society explained that â€œdisasterâ€
was a suitable symbol for 2018 in Japan because the kanji character touched
people's lives in different ways:

