Each December, the Kanji of the Year is announced at historic Kiyomizu-dera, a
temple and UNESCO world heritage site in Kyoto, first established 1,300 years
ago. Reverend [Mori
Seihan](https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%A3%AE%E6%B8%85%E7%AF%84), the chief
abbot of the temple, typically unveils the Kanji of the Year by writing it in
traditional calligraphy, captured in this video of the 2018 ceremony:

As Japan prepares for the [abdication of its current
emperor](https://asia.nikkei.com/Politics/Japanese-emperor-s-
abdication-6-things-to-know) in May 2019, thereby ending the [Heisei
Era](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heisei_period)[ as it makes the transition
to a new
emperor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_imperial_transition,_2019),
the second most popular Chinese character in this year's poll was â€œheiâ€ (å¹³).
â€œHeiâ€ is one of two kanji that make up â€œHeiseiâ€ ( **å¹³** æˆ), the name of the
reign of the current Emperor of Japan, who is typically known in the rest of
the world as [Akihito](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akihito):

